data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout Enforcement**

Your code uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill a thread exceeding a deadline. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it simply doesn't work.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` must cooperate with cancellation (recommended)

Change the signature to accept a token so work can actually stop:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then check the token inside their work:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---------|------------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work` never checks the token, it keeps running in the background even after you've thrown `TimeoutException`. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always `using`. |
| **`Task.Run` doesn't interrupt blocking calls** | `Thread.Sleep`, synchronous I/O, etc. won't respond to the token. Use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the orchestration boundary (here, to wrap as `TimeoutException`). |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If you truly cannot modify `work` to check a token, the only .NET 8 equivalent of "kill it" is to run it in a **separate process** and call `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process forced termination. |

---

### What was removed

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 Replacement |
|----|-----|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` (via timeout) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed — not needed with cooperative model |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `Task.WaitAsync(token)` |
